            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this IBU homebrew calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates the bitterness of your beer in International
                Bitterness Units (IBU) using either the Tinseth or Rager
                formula. It supports:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Multiple hop additions at different times</li>
                <li>Pellet vs. whole/leaf hops (pellet boost)</li>
                <li>Boil, whirlpool/hop‑stand, and flameout additions</li>
                <li>Metric and US units (liters/gallons, grams/ounces)</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Tinseth IBU formula</h3>
              <p>
                The Tinseth model is widely used by homebrewers and commercial
                breweries. For each hop addition:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Utilization</strong> (Tinseth):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ U = 1.65 \times 0.000125^{(OG - 1)} \times \frac{1 -
                  e^{-0.04 \times t}}{4.15} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  where \(OG\) is original gravity and \(t\) is boil time in
                  minutes.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>IBU contribution of one addition:</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ IBU = \frac{U \times \alpha \times W \times 1000}{V} \]
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(\alpha\): alpha acid fraction (e.g. 10% = 0.10)</li>
                  <li>\(W\): hop weight in grams</li>
                  <li>\(V\): batch volume in liters</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Rager IBU formula</h3>
              <p>
                The Rager method often yields slightly higher IBUs, especially
                for very bitter beers. In simplified form:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Gravity adjustment:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ G_f = \begin{cases} 0 & \text{if } OG \le 1.050 \\ \frac{OG
                  - 1.050}{0.2} & \text{if } OG &gt; 1.050 \end{cases} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Utilization:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ U = \frac{18.11 + 13.86 \tanh\left(\frac{t -
                  31.32}{18.27}\right)}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>IBU:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ IBU = \frac{U \times \alpha \times W \times 7462}{V \times
                  (1 + G_f)} \]
                </p>
                <p>where \(W\) is in ounces and \(V\) in US gallons.</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Pellet vs. whole hops</h3>
              <p>
                Pellet hops typically yield slightly higher utilization than
                whole/leaf hops. This calculator applies a default 10%
                utilization boost for pellets. If you prefer a different factor,
                you can mentally adjust your target IBUs or tweak the alpha acid
                percentage.
              </p>

              <h3>Whirlpool and hop‑stand IBUs</h3>
              <p>
                When hops are added after flameout at temperatures below
                boiling, they still isomerize alpha acids, but at a reduced
                rate. To approximate this, we:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Treat whirlpool time as an “effective boil time”</li>
                <li>
                  Scale utilization by a temperature factor between 0 and 1
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Temperature factor (approximate):</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ f_T = \min\left(1,\; \max\left(0,\; \frac{T -
                  60}{40}\right)\right) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  where \(T\) is whirlpool temperature in °C (60–100&nbsp;°C).
                </p>
                <p>Effective utilization for whirlpool additions:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ U_{\text{whirlpool}} = f_T \times U_{\text{Tinseth}}(t) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Typical IBU ranges by style</h2>
              <p>
                Use these ranges as a starting point when designing your recipe:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>American light lager:</strong> 8–15 IBU</li>
                <li><strong>Wheat beer / Blonde ale:</strong> 10–20 IBU</li>
                <li><strong>Pale ale:</strong> 25–40 IBU</li>
                <li><strong>American IPA:</strong> 40–70 IBU</li>
                <li><strong>Double / Imperial IPA:</strong> 60–100+ IBU</li>
                <li><strong>Porter / Stout:</strong> 25–45 IBU</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Remember that perceived bitterness also depends on malt
                sweetness, alcohol, water chemistry, and late/dry hopping, not
                just the lab‑measured IBU.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Does dry hopping increase IBU?</h3>
              <p>
                Dry hopping can increase measured IBUs slightly due to
                polyphenols and oxidation products, but the effect is small
                compared to boil or hot‑side additions. Dry hops mainly add
                aroma and perceived bitterness rather than large IBU changes, so
                this calculator does not include a separate dry hop IBU model.
              </p>

              <h3>Why do different calculators give different IBU numbers?</h3>
              <p>
                Different tools may use Tinseth, Rager, Garetz, or custom
                utilization curves, and they may treat whirlpool additions
                differently. Even lab measurements can vary. Use one consistent
                method for your recipes and calibrate by taste over a few
                batches.
              </p>

              <h3>
                How accurate are IBU estimates for very high‑gravity or NEIPA
                recipes?
              </h3>
              <p>
                All common IBU formulas are approximations. For very high
                gravity, heavily hopped, or hazy beers, the relationship between
                calculated and perceived bitterness becomes less linear. Use the
                numbers as a guide, but rely on your own tasting notes to dial
                in future batches.
              </p>
